</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB73696C613FFD80DD3DE3FFD08F889" blockId="91.[151,1436,1796,2031]" box="[151,648,1826,1851]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Description as for the only included species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C312651DC613FFD80D83DE5BFAA9F85D" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB73696C613FFD80D83DE5BFC3BF815" blockId="91.[151,1436,1796,2031]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C613FFD80D83DE5BFECFF8ED" bold="true" box="[199,335,1862,1887]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Comments.</emphasis>
This genus is described for a single, highly distinctive species. It can be distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D15C613FFD80DD3DE77FED0F831" box="[151,336,1898,1923]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Archiborborinae">Archiborborinae</taxonomicName>
by the greatly enlarged thoracic and leg bristles (
<figureCitation id="13332A13C613FFD80E31DE77FC47F831" box="[885,967,1898,1923]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1695,1718]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,226,1646]" captionTargetId="figure-79@10.[151,1436,193,1646]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Archiborborine adults, habitus photos: (7) Antrops truncipennis, female, Bird Island, South Georgia Islands; (8) A. siberia, male holotype, Yungas de la Siberia, Bolivia; (9) A. tetrastichus, male paratype, Quito–Baeza pass; (10) Photoantrops echinus, male holotype, SierrAzul Lodge, Ecuador; (11) Coloantrops daedalus, female paratype, Laraquete, Chile; (12) Poecilantrops psilosternum, female paratype, Nova Friburgo, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6507451" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6507451/files/figure.png" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), the lack of ocellar bristles, presence of a single ocellar bristle, and syntergite 1+2 twice the width of tergites 3–5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB73696C613FFD80D83DEAFFAA9F85D" blockId="91.[151,1436,1796,2031]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
The genus name is formed from a combination of the Greek 
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C613FFD80ECFDEAEFC56F879" box="[907,982,1971,1995]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">photos</emphasis>
(light) and the genus name 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D15C613FFD8085ADEAEFAF6F878" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1909" box="[1310,1398,1971,1994]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Antrops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA84C613FFD8085ADEAEFAF6F878" box="[1310,1398,1971,1994]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Antrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in reference to the collection method of the 
<typeStatus id="54B38834C613FFD80F20DECAFD14F85D" box="[612,660,2007,2031]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">type</typeStatus>
species. It is masculine in accordance with ICZN 30.1.4.3.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
